HEADWORD: Iatromathematician
<hw>I*a`tro*math`e*ma*ti"cian</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr.
<?/ physician + E. <ets>mathematician</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Hist.
Med.)</fld> <def>One of a school of physicians in Italy, about the
middle of the 17th century, who tried to apply the laws of mechanics and
mathematics to the human body, and hence were eager student of anatomy;
-- opposed to the <xex>iatrochemists</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Iberian</ent>⟦br⟧
